DIFFERENTIATION OF OPTICAL SIGNALS USING AN INTEGRATED "METAL-DIELECTRIC-METAL" STRUCTURE

Abstract

The possibilities of using integrated "metal-dielectric-metal" structures located in a plane-parallel dielectric waveguide for optical differentiation of the first and second order of the incident optical beam profile in reflection are analyzed. According to the presented results of numerical modeling within the framework of the electromagnetic diffraction theory, the studied structures can perform spatial differentiation operations with high quality. The obtained results can find application in new systems of optical information processing and optical computing based on integrated nanophotonic structures.

DOI: 10.31857/S0367676524010015, EDN: SBPYGC

INTRODUCTION

Differentiation of optical signals plays an important role in analog optical information processing, allowing to extract necessary information about the spatial and temporal dynamics of optical signals. In connection with the development of nanotechnology and growing interest in high-speed and compact optical information processing systems, the development of new nanophotonic structures for differentiating optical signals appears to be an important and relevant task.
The transformation of an optical signal that occurs when it is reflected or passes through a diffractive structure can be considered as a transformation performed by a linear system. The transfer function (TF) of this system is determined by the reflection or transmission coefficient of the structure, considered as a function of angular and (or) spatial frequency [1-3]. Since the TF of an ideal differentiator has a zero at the central (carrier) frequency, optical differentiation requires that the reflection or transmission spectrum of the diffractive structure contains zeros. As a rule, the zeros of reflection and transmission are due to resonant effects associated with the excitation of the structure's eigenmodes. This is why various resonant structures, in particular, resonant diffraction gratings [1, 2] and layered structures [4-7], are widely used for differentiation.
Recent studies by the authors of this work have shown that simple three-layer "metal-dielectric-metal" (MDM) structures allow optical computation of the first derivative with respect to the spatial variable or in time in reflection [5, 6]. It was also shown that "cascaded" MDM structures consisting of several single MDM structures allow the implementation of optical computation of n-th order derivatives [7]. It is important to note that in a wide range of parameters, it is always possible to provide the zero reflection required for differentiation by selecting the thicknesses of the MDM structure layers.
In this work, we consider the application of integral analogues of layered MDM structures, consisting of metal "strips" "immersed" in a plane-parallel waveguide, for optical differentiation of beams propagating in the waveguide. Two types of integral MDM structures are considered. The first type is a "single" integral MDM structure consisting of two metal strips separated by a waveguide "segment" and possessing a first-order zero reflection. As shown below, this structure can be used for optical calculation of the first derivative of the incident beam profile propagating in the waveguide. The second type is a "double" integral MDM structure consisting of two sequentially arranged single MDM structures. This structure has a second-order zero and allows calculating the second-order derivative of the incident beam profile.

SINGLE INTEGRAL MDM STRUCTURE

The structure for calculating the first derivative consists of two metal strips "immersed" in a single-mode plane-parallel dielectric waveguide (Fig. ), the thickness of which for the examples considered below is 100 nm. In the examples considered, gallium phosphide is chosen as the waveguide material, silicon dioxide as the substrate, and air as the material of the area above the structure.

DOUBLE INTEGRAL MDM STRUCTURE

The structure proposed for calculating the second derivative consists of two MDM structures separated by a waveguide segment of a certain width (Fig. 1b). Let's consider the methodology and an example of calculating a double MDM structure. In [7], formulas are given for calculating "cascaded" layered MDM structures with a zero reflection of a given order. Condition (3) can be written similarly to (1), (2) in the form of two equalities of moduli and arguments. The method for calculating the parameters of a double MDM structure will also be similar to the method described above for calculating the parameters of a single MDM structure. The difference is that the parameters of the first MDM structure will be determined from the equality of moduli (the parameters of the second MDM structure are assumed to be fixed), and the width of the waveguide segment between the structures [7] will be determined from the equality of arguments. Note that the calculation of a double integral MDM structure is much more time-consuming in terms of computation time compared to the case of non-integral layered structures designed to work with radiation propagating in free space.

CONCLUSION

The optical performance of spatial differentiation operations using MDM structures integrated into a plane-parallel dielectric waveguide has been investigated. Single and double MDM structures with first- and second-order reflection zeros, respectively, have been calculated. The results of rigorous numerical modeling show that the calculated structures allow performing first- and second-order differentiation operations with high quality. The obtained results can find application in the development of new systems for optical information processing and analog optical computing based on integrated nanophotonic structures.

Differentiation of optical signals using an integrated metal-dielectric-metal structure

A. I. Kashapov , E. A. Bezus , D. A. Bykov , L. L. Doskolovich Image Processing Systems Institute, National Research Centre "Kurchatov Institute", Samara, 443001, Russia Samara National Research University, 443086, Samara, Russia *e-mail: ar.kashapov@outlook.com

We consider optical properties of integrated metal-dielectric-metal structures embedded in a dielectric slab waveguide and their application to the problems of first- and second-order optical differentiation of the profile of the incident optical beam in reflection. According to the presented numerical simulation results, the investigated structures enable performing the spatial differentiation operation with high quality. The presented results may find application in novel systems for optical information processing and analog optical computing based on integrated nanophotonic structures.
Keywords: metal-dielectric-metal structure, slab waveguide, optical differentiation, resonances in integrated structures.
